In [20]:
xtab = pd.crosstab(index=data['heart_disease'], columns=data['stroke'])

barplot = xtab.plot.bar(rot=0, title='Heart Disease Cross Tabulation with Stroke', ylabel = "Count")

From the cross tabulation of heart disease and stroke we can see in the table below more clearly that a higher percentage of people that had heart disease also had a stroke compared to the people who did not have heart disease.

In [26]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
plt.xlabel("Age")
plt.ylabel("BMI")
plt.title("Age versus BMI with Color Indicating Stroke")

scatter1 = ax.scatter(data['age'], data['bmi'], c = data['stroke'], alpha = 0.3)
ax.legend(*scatter1.legend_elements(), loc='upper right', title="Stroke")
plt.show()

The scatter plot above of age versis BMI with color indicating if the patient experienced a stroke we can see more yellow dots with older people. There is not a clear trend that higher BMI patients have a higher frequency of strokes from this visualization.

In [27]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
plt.xlabel("Age")
plt.ylabel("Avg Glucose Level")
plt.title("Age versus Glucose Level with Color Indicating Stroke")

scatter1 = ax.scatter(data['age'], data['avg_glucose_level'], c = data['stroke'], alpha = 0.3)
ax.legend(*scatter1.legend_elements(), loc='upper right', title="Stroke")
plt.show()

The scatter plot above of age and average glucose level there seems to be a trend of higher glucose levels and an increased age see more patients with a stroke. The data is fairly dense at lower glucose levels and even with the transparent dots we could be missing a trend at these lower levels.

In [28]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
plt.xlabel("BMI")
plt.ylabel("Avg Glucose Level")
plt.title("BMI versus Glucose Level with Color Indicating Stroke")

scatter1 = ax.scatter(data['bmi'], data['avg_glucose_level'], c = data['stroke'], alpha = 0.3)
ax.legend(*scatter1.legend_elements(), loc='upper right', title="Stroke")
plt.show()

The above plot shows BMI versus average glucose and we can see that elevated glucose levels have more yellow dots or patients with a stroke. Similar to the last plot the data is very dense at lower glucose levels so we could be missing some trends in this visualization.
